Comunicate Data Findings¶

Ford GoBike is a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. Using Python data science and data visualization libraries this documents will explore the data from individual rides in hopes of understanding the datas structure, oddities, patterns and relationships within the dataset

Dataset Overview¶

The data consists of features of approximately 174,000 rides. There are 15 variables within the dataset, including ride duration, ride start and end time and user demographic info such as user type, gender and birth year.

From the above, we can idenify that there are some data tidynss and quality issues within our dataset.

Data issues:¶

  1. Missing data in the membership info, start and end trip locations
  2. start_time saved as a string instead of datetime data type
  3. end_time saved as a string instead of datetime data type
  4. user_type is saved as a string and can be changed to categorical data type
  5. member_birth_year is saved as a float and can be changed to an int
  6. member_gender is saved as a string and can be changed to categorical data type
  7. bike_share_for_all_trip is saved as a string and can be changed to categorical data type

What is the structure of the dataset?¶

The dataset contains 183412 rides across the month of Feburary 2019 with 16 features which can be categorised into:

  1. Date, time and duration of each trip
  2. Start locations
  3. End locations
  4. Bike ID
  5. User demographic (Age, Gender, user type, bike sharing)

I am interested in mapping out the usage of the bikes by the hour and seeing

4. Univariate Exploration¶

First, let's look at the main variable ride duration in the ride duration variable.

In [28]:
# the ride duration has a long right tailed distribution, lets use a log scale to investigate 

# creating the log binsize and tick lables
binsize = 0.025
bins = 10 ** np.arange(0, np.log10(df_copy['duration_min'].max())+binsize, binsize)
ticks = [1, 3 ,10, 30, 100, 300, 1000]
labels = ['{}'.format(i) for i in ticks]

# Plotting the log scale distribution
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
sns.histplot(data = df_copy, x = 'duration_min', bins=bins, color = blue)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks(ticks, labels)

plt.xlabel('Ride duration (minutes)')
plt.title('Log-scale No. of rides by duration');

Observation:

Ride duration has a long-tailed distribution, with many rides having a low ride duration. It may be interesting to find out who are the users taking the longer bike rides

When plotted on a log-scale, it takes on a right-skewed unimodal distribution, with a peak around 7 and 12 minutes. Along the right-tail distribution, the ride durations go up to over 1000 minutes, which seem unlikely for a bike sharing programme. So, let's remove the outliers in the long right tail, by trimming the duration_min variable to the 99th percentile.

In [29]:
#finding the 99th percentile duration
percentile = df_copy['duration_min'].quantile(0.99)

# Dropping rows greater than the 99th percentile
df_copy = df_copy[df_copy['duration_min'] <= percentile]

With that done, let's take a look athe the age distribution of our dataset.

In [30]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))
sns.boxplot(data = df_copy, x = 'member_age')
plt.xlabel("User's Age");

Observation:

Age of users seems to have a right-tailed distribution, with the median age being around 31 years old.

The youngest users are aged 18 and the oldest being 54; the age floor may be due to requirements to sign up for the bike sharing program and the age ceiling from our data cleaning. We can also observe that the median age of the user is around 31 with the Q1 and Q3 of about 27 and 37 respectively.

Lets get a different look at the distribution density of age through a histogram.

Observation:

As expected from the previous box plot, the majority of users are between the 25 - 40 age range, with much fewer users above the age of 40, with the number of users lowering as age increases.

Observation:

Overall, as we have already observed, customers have a higher ride duration compared to subscribers. Also, the variability in customer ride duration during non-peak hours become much more evident when comparing it across days, with a large amount of variability in ride duration distributions from 10pm till 8am.

For customers, the ride duration across the days do not seem to follow any specific distribution, with varying median ride duration and distributions across the days. Interestingly, customers are going on longer ride during the weekends as compared to rides on the weekday.

For subscribers, a more interesting observation can be made about the median ride duration between weekdays and weekends. On weekdays, the ride duration follows the distributions that we have observed thus far, with ride duration medians around 7 mins with peaks at around 8am and 5pm. However, on the weekend, the average median ride duration increases to around 9 mins, with peak median ride durations happening during 12 noon to 2pm.

These observations further emphasise how ride duration may not be the best matrics for to guage overall usage of the bikes.

To get a better visualisation of bike usage, I would like to explore the total duration of bike ride for each hour across both user types. To achieve this, we will add the sum of ride durations, grouped by their starting hour; for every hour of each day. This should give us a more complete picture of the usage of the bikes across each week.

In [48]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))

plt.subplot(2,1,1)
hm_cust = df_copy.query('user_type == "Customer"').groupby(['day','start_hour'])['duration_min'].sum().reset_index()
hm_cust = hm_cust.pivot('day','start_hour','duration_min')
ax=sns.heatmap(hm_cust, cmap="YlGnBu")

plt.title('Total Ride Duration of All Customers')
plt.xlabel('')
plt.ylabel('Day of the week')
plt.yticks([0,1,2,3,4,5,6], ['Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', 'Sat', 'Sun'])

plt.subplot(2,1,2)
hm_subs = df_copy.query('user_type == "Subscriber"').groupby(['day','start_hour'])['duration_min'].sum().reset_index()
hm_subs = hm_subs.pivot('day','start_hour','duration_min')
ax=sns.heatmap(hm_subs, cmap="YlGnBu")

plt.title('Total Ride Duration of All Subscribers')
plt.xlabel('Start Hour')
plt.ylabel('Day of the week')
plt.yticks([0,1,2,3,4,5,6], ['Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', 'Sat', 'Sun']);

Observation: From the heatmaps above, the overall usage of bikes for both customers and subscribers becomes much clearer. From before, we know that customers generally take longer individual rides. However, due to the large number of subscribers over customers, the total usage of bikes is significantly higher for subscribers.

For customers during the weekdays, it appears that the highest usage of bikes has two peaks around 7am to 9am and 4pm to 6pm. On weekends however, the customers riding behaviours shift to a heavier usage between 1am to 5pm.

For subscribers on weekdays, it is clear that there are 2 peak periods of bike usage: 7am to 9am and 4pm to 7pm; with the highest usage happening at 8am and 5pm. Like their fellow user type, subscribers usage also changes during the weekends. Notably, subscribers bike usage is significantly less during weekends. For subscribers who do use the bikes on weekends, they tend to do so from 10am to 5pm.

What are some of the relationships observed in this part of the investigation?¶

While exploring ride duration against the daily hours, it became clear that ride duration alone could not provide a full picture into the usage off the bikes. Although ride duration was able provided some insight into the difference in usage between customers, ultimately the large difference in the number of user types would play a large role when exploring the bike usage.

When we explored the total ride duration by all users across the hours of each day, the usage across the hours of the week became very clear. We were also able to observe a significant difference in overall bike usage patterns between weekdays and weekends.
